    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9c199ec9-ad6e-49fa-af94-b55d85ab0ae9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an energetic 8-year-old boy with bright brown eyes and a mop of dark curly hair. He attends third grade at a local elementary school where he loves math and drawing. Outside of school, {patientName} is passionate about soccer, playing for a neighborhood youth team on weekends, and enjoys video games and building LEGO sets with his older brother. He lives with both parents and his 11-year-old brother in a suburban home.\n\nToday, {patientName} appears visibly uncomfortable, sitting quietly on the examination table with a flushed face and slightly glassy eyes. He is dressed in his school uniform and is clutching a small stuffed dinosaur. He keeps swallowing carefully, wincing each time, and his mother reports he has barely touched his breakfast or lunch today.\n\nOn examination, {patientName} is febrile with a temperature of 38.7°C. His throat is visibly red and inflamed, with mild tonsillar enlargement and no exudate noted. There is mild bilateral cervical lymphadenopathy on palpation. His voice sounds slightly hoarse and he intermittently complains of an earache on the right side. He denies cough or runny nose.\n\n{patientName}'s mother explains that his symptoms started two days ago with a sore throat and low-grade fever, and that several of his classmates have recently been sick with similar complaints. She is concerned and has been giving him honey and warm tea, but the fever has persisted. He attends afterschool soccer practice three times a week and was unable to attend the last session due to feeling unwell.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is described as a social and cheerful child who has a good appetite under normal circumstances. His diet consists mostly of home-cooked meals, with an occasional fast-food treat on weekends. He shares a bedroom with his brother and the family has a pet dog. His mother mentions he tends to get a sore throat once or twice a year, especially in autumn and winter."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:16442c73-7617-4479-9e9e-ab5037a82286",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a generally unremarkable medical history. He was born at term via normal vaginal delivery with no neonatal complications. He is up to date with all childhood vaccinations according to the national immunization schedule, including MMR, varicella, and influenza.\n\n{patientName} has had recurrent episodes of sore throat — approximately once or twice per year — since starting school, all of which have resolved without hospitalization. He had one episode of otitis media at age 5, managed successfully with a short course of antibiotics. There is no history of hospitalization, surgery, or chronic illness.\n\n{patientName} has a known mild allergy to amoxicillin (skin rash), which has been documented since age 6. He has no known food allergies. He takes no regular medications and has no history of asthma or atopic dermatitis. His growth and development have been appropriate for his age. His BMI is within the healthy range for his age and sex."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
